          "body": "Psalm 54:6 is the most theologically daring verse in the Psalm: 'Willingly I will sacrifice to You; I will give thanks to Your name, O LORD, for it is good.' David vows the sacrifice before 54:7 has happened. The Ziphites have not been dealt with. Saul's army is still in the field. The deliverance is not yet visible. And David is already pledging a freewill offering and public thanksgiving. This is not presumption — it is the fruit of trust that has genuinely landed on the character of God. The *nedavah* (freewill offering) is by definition not legally required: it is the spontaneous, joyful gift of a heart that has found God's name to be 'good' and cannot help but respond. The writer of Hebrews picks up this sacrificial language for the New Covenant: 'Through Him then let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God, that is, the fruit of lips that give thanks to His name' (Hebrews 13:15). Psalm 54:6 is the Old Covenant form of that continuous sacrifice."
