          "title": "Deliverance declared — the perfect-tense close",
          "body": "The Psalm closes in 54:7 with two perfect-tense verbs: 'He has delivered me from all trouble, and my eye has looked with satisfaction upon my enemies.' The Hebrew perfect here is either a statement of completed past deliverance (the Psalm was completed after the event of 1 Samuel 26, when David spared Saul's life and Saul withdrew) or the 'prophetic perfect' — a declaration of future certainty so firm it is expressed as already accomplished. Either reading confirms what the Psalm has been building toward: the petitioner who cried 'save me' in 54:1 can declare 'He has delivered me' in 54:7 because the God invoked by name in 54:1 has been confessed as helper in 54:4 and praised in 54:6. The trajectory is complete. The eye that looks 'with satisfaction upon my enemies' is not the eye of gloating vengeance — the same Hebrew root (*ra'ah*) is used for the satisfaction of seeing justice done, the relief that follows when the threat has been removed and God's faithfulness vindicated. The Psalm that began with the extremity of fugitive David ends with the vindicated confidence of a man whose God has proved exactly as good as His name."
